<div id="head">
  <h1>Googler</h1>
  <span class="description">All the Googles at your fingertips.</span>
</div>
<div class="content">

<p>Googler makes it easy to search the Google you want, when you want. Give a prefix like <code>news:</code> (as in <code>news:iraq</code>) to search Google News or <code>images:</code> to search images. Prefix with <code>mid:</code> to retrieve a news messages from Google Groups or <code>?</code> (as in <code>?aaron</code>) to do an "I'm Feeling Lucky" search.</p>

<form method="get" action="googler">
<input name="q" type="text" /> <input type="submit" value="Search!" /> (<a href="_googler.py">Python source code</a>)
</form>

<p>If you're a IE/Mac user, you can <a href="http://www.macslash.com/articles/01/10/10/1828238.shtml">integrate Googler into your address bar</a> (just use <code><a href="googler.cgi?secret=on&amp;q=">http://www.aaronsw.com/2002/googler.cgi?secret=on&q=</a></code> as your magic string). If you like this, you might also like <a href="dtrt">ADTRT</a>, which does everything Googler does and more! Also, check out <a href="http://google.blogspace.com/">the Google Weblog</a> for more Google tips and tricks.</p>

</div>
